<div id="review_1560570074" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1560570074" />
    <a title="Tom O&#39;Brien" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6812428-tom-o-brien"><img alt="Tom O&#39;Brien" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1604864080p2/6812428.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1560570074?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom O&#39;Brien" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom O&#39;Brien" href="/user/show/6812428-tom-o-brien">Tom O&#39;Brien</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6812428-tom-o-brien?shelf=plays">plays</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1560570074" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13273561775414059616">A bizarre but simple question; &apos;How could he not know?&apos; with a simple but complex answer; he didn&apos;t want to and he didn&apos;t want him to. And for so long? Well what they did on one night they might have done for a thousand nights, with only skilful variations. The play also makes much more of the question of illusion, assumption, desire and deceit than mechanics in any case. <br/><br/>The sex, for all the scandal it brought, was only a part of it. The playwright frequently makes the link between sex as power</span>
  <span id="freeText13273561775414059616" style="display:none">A bizarre but simple question; 'How could he not know?' with a simple but complex answer; he didn't want to and he didn't want him to. And for so long? Well what they did on one night they might have done for a thousand nights, with only skilful variations. The play also makes much more of the question of illusion, assumption, desire and deceit than mechanics in any case. <br /><br />The sex, for all the scandal it brought, was only a part of it. The playwright frequently makes the link between sex as power and vice versa. The political parallels are appropriately unsubtle, considering it was Vietnam, considering it is the West and China, considering it is Men and their (our) idea of women.<br /><br />Unashamedly theatrical, if not operatic, it benefits from all that emotion, flowing from every character.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13273561775414059616" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


